'''Clairève''' or '''Claireve Grandjouan''' (10 October 1929 – 1982) was a French-born American archaeologist.<ref name="nyt-obit">{{cite news|title=Claireve Grandjouan, 52, Dies; Taught Archeology at Hunter|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/08/obituaries/claireve-grandjouan-52-dies-taught-archeology-at-hunter.html|accessdate=2 April 2018|work=New York Times|date=1982}}</ref><ref name="williams">{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Shellie|editor1-last=de Grummond|editor1-first=Nancy Thomson|title=Encyclopedia of the History of Classical Archaeology|date=2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134268542|page=531|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LeE4CQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA531&pg=PA531#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=2 April 2018|chapter=Grandjouan, Claireve (1929-1982)}}</ref><ref name="venit">{{cite web|last1=Venit|first1=Marjorie Susan|title=Claireve Grandjouan|url=http://www.brown.edu/Research/Breaking_Ground/results.php?d=1&first=Claireve&last=Grandjouan|website=Breaking Ground: Women in Old World Archeology|publisher=Brown University|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=venit-biog>{{cite book|last1=Venit|first1=Marjorie Susan|title=Biography of Clairèeve Grandjouan|publisher=Breaking Ground: Women in Old World Archeology|url=http://www.brown.edu/Research/Breaking_Ground/bios/Grandjouan_Claireve.pdf|accessdate=2 April 2018 }} ''Includes full text of Grandjouan's "The Dormouse Caper" on pp 30–35''</ref><ref name="ridgway">{{cite journal|last1=Ridgway|first1=Brunilde Sismondo|title=Necrology: Claireve Grandjouan (1929–1982)|journal=American Journal of Archaeology|date=January 1983|volume=87|issue=1|pages=131–132|url=https://www.ajaonline.org/toc/871|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref>
She had a B.A. and Ph.D. from [[Bryn Mawr College]]. After working on excavations in Athens, she became General Secretary of the [[Archaeological Institute of America]] (1962–1968) and editor of its ''Bulletin'', while teaching at [[New York University]] (1963–1968). She then taught at [[Hunter College]] from 1968, becoming chairman of classical and Oriental studies in 1968 and full professor in 1981.<ref name=nyt-obit /><ref name=venit />
She frequently spoke in public, described as "Stimulating, amusing, and well informed on a wide variety of area studies" and "a consummate educator".<ref name=venit />
She was a lively personality, and wrote fiction as well as academic papers, including a spoof entitled "The Dormouse Caper" which is described as showing her views on "teaching, scholarship and life".<ref name=venit-biog />
==Selected publications== *{{cite book | last=Grandjouan | first=Clairève|title=Plastic Lamps and Terracottas of the Roman Period|place= Princeton|publisher= American School of Classical Studies|date= 1961|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=RUJoAAAAMAAJ&dq=inauthor%3A%22Clair%C3%A8ve+Grandjouan%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=smith}} *{{cite book| last=Grandjouan | first=Clairève | title=Hellenistic Relief Molds from the Athenian Agora|place= Princeton|publisher= American School of Classical Studies|date=1989|isbn=9780876615232 | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tzYp4dm2T20C&printsec=frontcover&dq=inauthor:%22Clair%C3%A8ve+Grandjouan%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH5f2tmKXaAhVBQMAKHWUEDqkQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q&f=false}}(completed by Eileen Markson and Susan I. Rotroff)
